\begin_layout Section
Spence Education (Signaling) Model and PBE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What's the motivation for signaling? Adverse selection: high types
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The high types in the Spence model are like the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

peaches
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the Akerlof model.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 want to overcome adverse selection and low types want to act like they
 are high types.
 Since we won't cover adverse selection until Econ 2020b, think of the Spence
 Education Model in the context of the high-low poker game where the low
 card holder tries to act like (pool with) the high card holder; or the
 Beer-Quiche game, where the weak type tries to act like the strong type.
 In Contract Theory, you can learn about what happens when there are a continuum
 of infinite types.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model Set-Up with Two Types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Potential employees (who are the agents and the Senders in this model) are
 of productivity type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\left\{ \theta_{L},\theta_{H}\right\} $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{L}<\theta_{H}$
\end_inset

 .
 The probability of an employee being a high productivity type given a level
 of education is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\theta_{H}|e)=\mu_{e}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Potential employees can send a signal 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in\left[0,\bar{e}\right]$
\end_inset

; and the cost of education for employees of type 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{L,H\}$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}(\cdot)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}'(\cdot)>0;\, c_{j}''(\cdot)>0;\, c_{j}(0)=0;\, c_{j}'(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape italic
Single-crossing assumption
\shape default

\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is also referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Spence-Mirlees
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 assumption and is the basis of many general equilibrium and game theoretic
 models.
 For a relatively straightforward application of the single crossing assumption
 and its derivation, see Shleifer and Wolfenson (2003, Journal of Financial
 Economics).
\end_layout

\end_inset

: assume that the marginal cost of eduction is greater for the low types
 than the high types for all levels of education.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Appendix A-1.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
c_{H}'(e)<c_{L}'(e)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The utility for employee 
\begin_inset Formula $j\in\{L,H\}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
u_{j}(w,e) & = & w(e)-c_{j}(e)\\
u(w,e|\theta) & = & w(e)-c(e|\theta)\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We further assume a competitive market for employees and so wage is equal
 to marginal productivity, which in turn is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 for an employee of type 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 In short, 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
w_{L} & = & \theta_{L}\\
w_{H} & = & \theta_{H}.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

However, if the employer does not know the type of employee, then the employer
 sets wage equal to the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 given the observable value of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
w(e)=\mathbb{E}\left[\theta|e\right]=\mu_{e}\theta_{H}+(1-\mu_{e})\theta_{L}.\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Game Theoretic Application
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the set up above, what equilibrium concept would work? BNE and PBE
 both are acceptable.
 However, PBE is more applicable since wage is bounded by the productivity
 of the employee and because it makes sense to explicitly state the beliefs
 of the employer (or Receiver) on and off the equilibrium path.
 Therefore, we're going to focus on PBE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall the requirements of PBE:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Beliefs 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e}$
\end_inset

 assigned to each node in an information set on the equilibrium path.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Given these beliefs, players best respond in each information set (sequential
 rationality).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Beliefs consistent with Bayes' Rule on the equilibrium path.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Where possible, beliefs off the equilibrium path are consistent with the
 equilibrium candidate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall also that in our signaling models (including the Beer-Quiche game),
 we had pooling, separating, and partial pooling equilibrium.
 The same should apply to this model as well.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's consider the following example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
A professor (the principal, receiver, or employer) wants to hire students
 (the agent, sender, or employee) as RAs for the summer.
 The relevant signal is the average score on econometrics problem sets:
 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in[0,100].$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
The current set up is a bit unrealistic in that the signal (or the problem
 sets) does not increase marginal productivity.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the Gibbons (1992) version of the Spence education model, education 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 increases the productivity---
\shape italic
i.e.

\shape default
 total production 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is a function of the employee's type and education: 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{e}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{\theta}>0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Let's assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{H}=\$10,000$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{L}=\$5,000$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{H}(e)=e^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{L}(e)=2e^{2}$
\end_inset

; and 
\shape italic
ex ante
\shape default
 probabilities are 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(H)=\frac{4}{5}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L)=\frac{1}{5}$
\end_inset

.
 Then student's optimization problem is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
\begin_inset Formula \[
\max_{e}u_{j}(e)=w(e)-c_{j}(e),\,\forall j\in\left\{ L,H\right\} .\]

\end_inset

If the employer (professor) was able to distinguish between the two types
 of students and the competitive market assumption holds, what is the optimal
 level of education for each type? Do you see that it is: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
e_{L}^{FB}=e_{H}^{FB}=0.\]

\end_inset

In Contract Theory, we denote this no information asymmetry level of education
 with the superscript 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

FB
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or first-best.
 It is the first best in the sense that it is the Pareto optimal outcome.
 Do you see why? If not, review the asymmetric information model below and
 then return to this question.
 What does this tell us about the signal? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Separating Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a separating equilibrium, the high types choose 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{H}>0$
\end_inset

 and the low types choose 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{L}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Why would the low type of employee choose a level of education greater
 than 0? Because education is costly, it would be profitable for the low
 type to increase education greater than 0 if and only if it would increase
 the wage she would receive, and hence make her better off.
 Since we're in a separating equilibrium, it must be the case that the low
 type invest 0 in education (and has no incentive to deviate to a higher
 level of education).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we assume a competitive labor market, 
\begin_inset Formula $w(e_{H})=\theta_{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w(e_{L}=0)=\theta_{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Now we can solve for the PBE using each employee types' Incentive Compatibility
 Constraints (ICC):
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the lectures, Elon did not specifically refer to the ICCs, but they were
 implied in the graphs.
 For our purposes, note that if ICCs are satisfied, no type wants to deviate
 and pretend to be another type.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $ICC_{H}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the ICC is normally written as: 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{H}=\arg\max_{e}u_{H}(e_{H})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{H}(e_{H})\geq u_{H}(e_{L}=0)\Rightarrow w(e_{H})-c_{H}(e_{H})\geq w(e_{L})-c_{H}(e_{L})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow10,000-e_{H}^{2}\geq5000-0\Rightarrow e_{H}\leq70.7$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $ICC_{L}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{L}(e_{L}=0)\geq u_{L}(e_{H})\Rightarrow w(0)-c_{L}(0)\geq w(e_{H})-c_{L}(e_{H})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow5,000-0\geq10,000-2e_{H}^{2}\Rightarrow e_{H}\geq50$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{H}\in\left[50,70.7\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Note that of these equilibrium levels of 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{H}$
\end_inset

, dominance refinement
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
More on this below.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 eliminates all of equilibria except for 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{H}=50$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To provide some intuition for the results above: for the high type of student,
 she wouldn't invest more than 70.7 in education because she'd be worse off
 than if she was considered a low type and received $5,000.
 Also for the high type, she'd want to invest more than 50 in education
 or else she would not be able to separate herself from the low type.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What beliefs of the Receiver (employer) on and off the equilibrium path
 get us the separating equilibrium? Consider the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mu(H|e)=\begin{cases}
1, & if\, e\geq e_{H}\\
0, & otherwise\end{cases}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See Appendix A-2 for a representation of the separating equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Pooling Equilibrium and PBE Refinements
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Pooling PBE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's assume that the initial (prior) distribution of high type and low
 type students is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(H)=\frac{4}{5}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(L)=\frac{1}{5}$
\end_inset

.
 If both the high and low types pooled at the same level of education 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}$
\end_inset

, then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathbb{E}\left[\theta|e_{p}\right]=\mu(H)\cdot\theta_{H}+\mu(L)\cdot\theta_{L}=9000.\]

\end_inset

At the pooling equilibrium, the low type must be as well off as if the low
 type received the low type payoff (
\begin_inset Formula $ICC_{L}$
\end_inset

 must hold):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
9000-c_{L}(e_{p})\geq5000-c_{L}(e_{L}=0)\Rightarrow9000-2e_{p}^{2}\geq5000\Rightarrow e_{p}\leq44.7.\]

\end_inset

Therefore, it is possible to sustain pooling for any 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}\leq44.7.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What beliefs of the Receiver (employer) on and off the equilibrium path
 get us the pooling equilibrium at education level 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}$
\end_inset

, which has to be less than 44.7? One possibility is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mu(H|e_{p})=\begin{cases}
\frac{4}{5}, & if\, e=e_{p}\in[0,\,44.7]\\
0, & otherwise\end{cases}\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now you should be able to figure out the sequentially rational strategies
 of the employer (professor) given these beliefs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See Appendix A-3 for a representation of the pooling equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Refinement of PBE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Dominance Refinement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
If possible, each player's reasonable beliefs off the equilibrium path should
 not assign positive probability to nodes that are reached only if another
 player plays 
\shape italic
a strategy that is strictly dominated beginning at some information set
\shape default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that this is different from not assigning positive probabilities to
 strictly dominated strategies.
 See Gibbons (1992, pp.
 232-35).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the context of the model above, given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall e\in[0,100],\, w(e)\in(5000,10000)$
\end_inset

, low types should never choose a level of education 
\begin_inset Formula $e>50$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\because$
\end_inset

even if a low type is able to deceive the employer into thinking she is
 a high type and get wage equal to 10000, if she increases her education
 to a level greater than 50, then she's worse off than if she just got the
 low type wage with zero education).
 This means that the probability of a high type for values of 
\begin_inset Formula $e>50$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(H|e>50)=1$
\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $w(e>50)=10,000$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider pooling at 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}=44.7$
\end_inset

: high types strictly prefer 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{H}=50+\epsilon$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I'm trying to be careful with the strict and weak inequalities, but we could
 just have said 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{H}=50$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $w=10,000$
\end_inset

 to a pooling equilibrium at 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}=44.7$
\end_inset

 and wage equal to 9000.
 With the dominance refinement which constrains the Receiver's off the equilibri
um path beliefs, we can see that:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
u_{H}(e & = & 50+\epsilon)=10,000-(50+\epsilon)^{2}\approx7500\\
 & > & u_{H}(e=e_{p}=44.7)=9000-(44.7)^{2}\approx7002.\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, there can be no pooling at 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}=44.7$
\end_inset

 once we apply the dominance refinement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider pooling at 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{p}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w(e_{p}=0)=9000$
\end_inset

.
 Here the high types will not be better off by deviating from the pooling
 equilibrium---
\shape italic
i.e.

\shape default
 payoff for the high types of pooling is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $9000-0^{2}=9000$
\end_inset

, which is greater than deviating to 
\begin_inset Formula $e=50+\epsilon\Rightarrow10000-\left(50+\epsilon\right)^{2}\approx7500$
\end_inset

.
 We can set 
\begin_inset Formula $w(e)$
\end_inset

 after defining the beliefs such that they satisfy the dominance refinement.
 For example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mu(H|e)=\begin{cases}
\frac{4}{5}, & if\, e=e_{p}=0\\
0, & if\, e\in(0,50]\\
1, & if\, e>50\end{cases}\]

\end_inset

which leads to the following sequentially rational strategies by the employer/Re
ceiver/principal:
